  "prompt": "How were nuclear reactor cores designed before the use of advanced computer modelling?",
  "response": "Before advanced computer modeling, nuclear reactor core design relied on several key methods:\n\n1. Analytical Calculations\n- Manual mathematical calculations using hand-performed neutron transport equations\n- Slide rules and mechanical calculators used for complex computations\n- Relied heavily on theoretical physics and neutron physics principles\n\n2. Experimental Modeling\n- Scale physical models testing neutron behavior\n- Critical assembly experiments\n- Prototype reactor tests to validate design assumptions\n\n3. Empirical Methods\n- Extensive use of empirical data from previous reactor designs\n- Systematic experimental data collection and analysis\n- Conservative design margins to account for uncertainties\n\n4. Graphical Tools\n- Manual graphing of neutron flux distributions\n- Hand-drawn charts and diagrams representing reactor core behavior\n- Slide charts for quick estimation of neutron interactions\n\n5. Simplified Computational Techniques\n- Early mechanical and analog computers\n- Basic numerical integration methods\n- Limited computational power compared to modern systems\n\n6. Extensive Safety Margins\n- Conservative design approaches\n- Overestimating potential risks\n- Multiple redundant safety systems\n\n7. Expert Knowledge\n- Reliance on experienced nuclear engineers and physicists\n- Collaborative design processes\n- Institutional knowledge transfer\n\nThese methods required significant human expertise and careful experimental validation.",
